{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_hagrid_ver01/data/sn83035602/00516993923/1945091401/0320.xml":{"full_text":"9 CPORTS\nf t OUT OF -oM\ns ADAM'S HAT 1\nXYV-P\nTHE DETROIT\nTIGERS, WORLDS\nCHAMPS IN _\nDARK\nDAYS\nFOR\nDETROIT\nIN\n1936/\nHANK\nGREENBERG,\nWHODTIED J\nFOR THE (V\nHOMERUN An\nCROWN IN\n1935 WAS OUT WITH A BROKEN WRIST,\n_ Sy ANDSCHOOLBOV\u2019 ROWE,\nace pitcher, had _\nA SORE SHOULDER.\nI'\nI\nI\nll\n-703.\nWERE 11\ngames\nout op\n1ST PLACE\nTHE I\nSAME\nDAY I\nTHAT\nJOE LOUIS\nMET HIS\nNEMESIS\nl\nI\n2\nMICKEY\n\u201cores COCHRANE,\nTIGER MGR.,\nSr HAD A NERVOUS\nP9 BREAKDOWN J\nAND WAS SENT AWAy a\nTO A RANCH? _\n1\njoe louis, DETROIT\u2019S dark DESTROYER, SUFFERED HiS ONLY PRO K.O.\nAT THE HANDS OF MAX SCHMELING, IN JUNE Of 1936..\nI\nJ 1\n\nLeggete \u201cL\u2019Araldo\"\nCongress Hard At It; Will Take Up\nImportant Bills By Mid September\n(Prepared by Congressman Frances P. Bolton's\nWashington Office in her absence)\nCONGRESS is hard at it, though\nno legislation can be ready for\nthe House to take up prior to the\nmiddle of Sep\ntember- mis is\nalso true of the\nSenate. Com\nmittees\nare\nstudying such\nimportant mat\nters as down\nward revision of\na p p ropriations\nwhich have been\nmade for war\nagencies, full\nemployment\n__ w c o m p e nsation\nproposals, revi\nMrs. Bolton\nsion of the ad\nministration of\nthe sale of surplus property, se\nlective service extension and reor\nganization of government depart\nments. A limited tax revision is\nalso a possibility.\nEmergency unemployment com\npensation may be the first acted\nupon as both the Ways and Means\nCommittee of the House and the\nFinance Committee of the Senate\nare working on legislation which\nwould include maritime and civil\nservice employees in providing\nminimum benefits of $25 per week\nfor a half year\u201426 weeks.\nCURTAILMENT of government\nwar activities is no simple\nproblem. Quite on the contrary,\nevery day since Japan capitulated\nhas brought additional knotty\nproblems. The following is an ex\nample: There is a general feeling\nthat the government should point\nthe way in \u201creconversion\u201d by eli\nminating war agencies with a view\nto getting back to what is looked\nupon as normal for the future. Not\na return to a pre-war basis, for\nthat cannot be. Changes have come\ndomestically as well as interna\ntionally\u2014new conditions, new re\nlations, new problems.\nEven in those cases where there\nis general agreement that agencies\nshould be discontinued immediate\nly, that is not always possible. In\nthe maze of government agencies\nand bureaus that were set up prior\nto the war and during wartime\nare those established by law, and\nmany, many others created by exe\ncutive order, and it is the latter\nthat have the government lawyers\nin a quandary.\n_ Where Cora as established\nCorg-as\nagencies by law, termination dates\nwere written in, so there is a defi\nnite legal basis for action in those\ninstances. Where the President\nacted by executive order, he did so\nin some cases as Commander-in\nI\nChief and with no mention of j\ntermination or time limits. Since\nthe President is Commander-in-\nChief in peace as well as in war,\na legal problem arises which must\nbe worked out carefully.\nl\ns\nE NAT OR VANDERBERG\u2019S\nsuggestion of a labor-manage\nment \u201cpeace\u201d conference is bear\ning fruit. The President has had\nthe heads of the \u201cBig Four\u201d\u2014the\nheads of the U. S. Chamber of\nCommerce, National Association\nof Manufacturers, American Fed\neration of Labor and the Congress\nof Industrial Organization to\ngether a time or two, and they are\nworking out an agenda for the\nproposed general labor-manage\nment conference to be held later\nin the year. If and when the con\nference materializes, it will be a\nbarometer by which forecasters\nwill gauge future labor-manage\nment relations.\nFORMER High Commissioner\nPaul McNutt has ronorted to\nPaul McNutt has reported to\nthe President on the Philippines.\nDetails are not known, but the\nreport is thought to cover some\nrather alarming conditions which\nwill strengthen the general opin\nion that to give the Islands their\nindependence next July as pro\nvided by existing statute would be\ndangerous.\nNative -leaders forced the issue\nat the time the present law was\nenacted. The Philippine situation\nis not helped any by the fact that\neight of our government agencies\nare operating there with no single\nhead or coordinated effort.\nGreater Cleveland is not\nto be as hard hit on unem\nployment as many other cities, ac\ncording to government authorities.\nExcept for the Akron area, north\neastern Ohio is not expected to\nsuffer as high a percentage of un\nemployment as other parts of\nOhio.\nThese sources predict that dur\ning the next six or eight weeks\nthe Ohio cities with greatest pro\nportionate unemployment will be\nAkron, Sandusky, Toledo, Lima,\nDayton, Springfieldand Cincinnati..\nI\nI\nFRANCES GIFFORD just\ncouldn\u2019t wait to get out and show\noff her fancy new bathing outfit\ndesigned especially by Irene. Rayon\nsilk jersey makes the body and the\n\u201ccord\u201d consists of padded strips of\nwhite linen. Frances is the fetch\ning schoolma'm in M-G-M's \"Ou\nVines Have Tender Grapes.\u201d\nAVVERTENZA\n****n,\n*A\n-71\nMr. JOE FONTANA \u00e8 il\nnuovo rappresentante genera\nle de L\u2019ARALDO, giornale\nsettimanale che si pubblica a\nCleveland, Ohio.\nDa ora in poi il predetto Mr.\nJoe Fontana \u00e8 autorizzato a\nsollecitare e collcttare abbo\nnamenti e avvisi, in ogni parte\ndegli Stati Uniti.\nNostro Agente\nIn California\nMr. JHON W. ZELLA \u00e8 A\ngente de L\u2019ARALDO in Cali\nfornia. Egli in questo Stato ha\npiena autorizzazione di solle\ncitare e collettare abbonamen\nti ed avvisi.\nOgni cortesia usata a Mr.\nZella sar\u00e0 molto apprezzata\ndalla nostra Amministrazione.\nPUBBLICIT\u00c0'\nECONOMICA\nsi VENDE\nCasa Duplex 5-5 di mattoni al No.\n25450 Lake Shore. Finestre a com\nbinazione; Doppio Garage; Riscal\ndamento a Gas; lotto 80x130 di\nbellissima veduta. Rivolgersi dal\nproprietario.\nCERCASI\nDonna italiana indipendente per\ncompagna, lavoro casalingo leg\ngiero, che sia interessata pi\u00f9 per\nla casa che per la paga. Occorrono\nreferenze.\nScrivere a M. Bravo\n4286 East 119, Cleveland, O.)s\"\nE\nI CLEVELAND GUIDE I\nChurches\nHOLY REDEEMER\n15712 KIPLING\nKE. 3313\nHOLY ROSARY\n12021 MAYFIELD RD. GA. 2995\nST. MARIAN\u2019S CHURCH\n2208 PETRARCA ROAD\nCEdar 0871\nST. ROCCO\n3205 FULTON ROAD\nWOodbine 8331\nST. JOHN\u2019S\nItalian Baptist Church\n12306 SOIKA AVENUE\nWAshngton 1237\nOUR LADY of MT. CARMEL\n11021 MT. CARMEL ROAD\nGArfield 5338\nST. ANTHONY\nST. BRIDGET\n2508 EAST 22nd STREET\nCHerry 6787\nOUR LADY OF\nMT. CARMEL MISSION'\n7104 DETROIT AVE.\nI\nGrocers\nC. G. GALLO\nLIBERTY CASH CARRY CO.\nHIGH LIFE WINES\n-X-0v.\nImported and Domestic Products\nBus.: PR. 9779 Res.: LO. 4453\n438-440 Woodland Avenue\nCHAS. ROBERTO\nWHOLESALE GROCER\n1020 Woodland Ave. CH. 0200\nCLEVELAND, O.\nOLIVO FOOD MARKET\nImported and Domestic\nMr. PAT VENTRA, Propr.\nGROCERIES MEAT MARKET\nI\n2649 E. 110th St.\nGArfield 3532\nFruit Vegetables\nPAOLO VOLPE\nDISTRIBUTOR OF FRUITS\nN. O. F. TERMINAL\nUNIT 11\nENdicott 5220\nMARTIN RINI\u2019S SONS, Inc.\nFRUIT and VEGETABLES\nN O. F. TERMINAL\nHEnderson 4671\nTHOMAS M. ZING ALE\nWholesale Fruits Vegetables\n1\nN. O. F. T.\nENdicott 7550\nI CLEVELAND CELERY\nMARKET COMPANY\nGrower, Receiver Distrib\u2019s\nFRUIT AND PRODUCE\n2633 E. 40th St ENdicott 2416\nJOHN MICELI Inc.\nLeading Celery Distributors\nN. O. F. T.\nUE. 2574-2575\nC. COMELLA INC.\nFruits Produce\n2629 E. 40th St.\nHE. 6656\nRestaurants\nI\nI\nAURORA\nLEADING\nITALIAN RESTAURANT\nSPAGHETTI TO TAKE HOME\n11316 Euclid Ave.\nRA. 1010\n1\nCHEF BOIARDI\nITALIAN RESTAURANT\nCucina all\u2019Italiana\nThree Minutes from Downtown\nWINE\u2014BEER\u2014LIQUOR\n917 Woodland Ave.\nPR. 9300\nForest Hill Cleaners\nTAILORS FURRIERS\n2-HOUR ODORLESS DRY CLEA